Data Governance – CDMP Study Notes
1. What is Data Governance?

Definition:
The exercise of authority, control, and shared decision-making over the management of data assets.

Purpose:

Ensure data is managed as a strategic asset.
Improve data quality.
Reduce risk and regulatory issues.
Define accountability and ownership.
Enable business value from data.

Key Principle:

Data Governance provides direction and oversight, while Data Management executes.

2. Data Governance Framework

Data Governance sits at the center of all data management disciplines.

Governance Responsibilities
Strategy alignment
Policy creation
Standards definition
Decision rights
Compliance monitoring
Issue escalation
Performance measurement
Governance Does NOT
Build ETL pipelines
Design databases
Develop reports
Perform operational data management

These belong to Data Management functions.

3. Data Governance Operating Model
Centralized

Single governing body controls data decisions.

Pros

Consistency
Standardization

Cons

Slow decision making
Decentralized

Business units govern their own data.

Pros

Flexibility

Cons

Inconsistent standards
Federated (Most Common)

Shared governance between enterprise and business units.

Pros

Balance of control and flexibility

Cons

Requires coordination

CDMP exams frequently favor Federated Governance as the preferred enterprise model.

4. Governance Organization Structure
Executive Sponsor

Provides funding and strategic direction.

Data Governance Council

Senior decision-making body.

Responsibilities:

Approve policies
Resolve conflicts
Prioritize initiatives
Data Stewardship Council

Coordinates stewardship activities.

Data Owners

Business accountability for data.

Responsibilities:

Approve access
Define quality expectations
Define business rules
Data Stewards

Manage data on behalf of owners.

Responsibilities:

Metadata
Data quality
Issue resolution
Data Custodians

Usually IT teams.

Responsibilities:

Storage
Security
Backup
Technical operations
